lines.text: IN THE DISTRICT COURT
HELD AT WELLINGTON
Decision No. 254 /2001
UNDER
The Accident Insurance Act 1998
AND
IN THE MATTER
of an appeal pursuant to section 152 of
the Act
BETWEEN
DOUGLAS JOHN THIMBLEBY
Appellant
(Appeal No. Al 64/01)
AND
ACCIDENT COMPENSATION
CORPORATION
Respondent
HEARD at Wellington on the 25" day of July 2001
DATE OF JUDGMENT |0 September 2001
APPEARANCES
J Miller for appellant
B A Corkill for respondent
JUDGMENT OF JUDGE A A P WILLY
Background
1] This case involves a short point of statutory interpretation. The question is whether s 40(2)
of the Accident Rehabilitation and Compensation Insurance Act 1996 (No 2) has retrospective
effect.
The Facts
2] On 5 December 1994 Mr Thimbleby who was then a fitter/welder injured his back in the
course of his employment. He was certified as incapacitated from 6 December 1994 and has
been unable to return to work in that occupation since that time.
3] Cover was granted to the appellant on the basis of enquiries which the Corporation made
of his employer and in 1995 the Corporation issued a decision which calculated Mr Thimbleby's
weekly compensation at a figure so low that it was advantageous for him to transfer to a social
welfare benefit. This he did in April 1995.
[4] In April 1998 the appellant sought to have his weekly compensation recalculated taking
into account a lesser number of weeks as a divisor that had been used by the Corporation as a
basis when first calculating his entitlements. The Corporation declined to undertake that
reassessment. An application for review was lodged. The Corporation considered in a letter of
10 September 1998 that the application was out of time and this was confirmed in a review
decision of 16 February 1999.
[5] In or about May 1999 the appellant again asked the Corporation to reconsider matters
having regard to the fact that in the relevant period he only worked for 17 weeks and not the 52
taken by the Corporation as its divisor in calculating his compensation entitlements.
[6] The Corporation responded by saying
"Therefore I have no alternative but to decline the request to reassess entitlement to
weekly compensation in accordance with the shorter earnings criteria set out in s 40
of the (1992 Act) as Mr Thimbleby was not in permanent employment at the time of
his incapacity."
[7] Mr Thimbleby applied for a review of that decision and on 21 January 2000 the reviewer
determined that he had no jurisdiction to hear a review because it was a decision declining to
reassess the appellant's weekly compensation. This, the reviewer found, had been dealt with in
the previous review decision of 10 February 1999 mentioned above.
[8] In January 2000 the appellant provided the respondent with further details of his 1994
earnings. From Robert Stone Limited he told the Corporation that he had earned $6,635.60
which had not been taken into account by the ACC in its 1995 weekly compensation calculation
decision. The Corporation accepted Mr Thimbleby's evidence and recalculated his weekly
compensation entitlement in a decision issued on 17 May 2000. In explaining that decision the
Corporation said:
"The long term weekly compensation assessment completed by the Corporation in
respect of incapacity in 1994 is correct. This assessment has been completed in the
same way in which it would have been if it had been completed in 1994.
The shorter earnings divisor in respect of 'the number of weeks or 13, whichever is
the greater', was as a result of the ARCI Amendment Act (No. 2) 1996. The effective
date for this amendment was 2 September 1996 and accordingly all weekly
compensation payments made beyond that date required recalculation. Those
reassessments were effective for weekly compensation paid from 2 September 1996
only."
[9] On 7 September 2000 Mr Miller, counsel for the appellant, advised the Corporation that in
his view its interpretation of the 1996 Amending Act was incorrect. Counsel contended that it
applied to the whole period of incapacity and not merely from the date upon which the legislation
came into force.
[10] The Corporation did not accept that view saying that:
"In this case we have applied s 40(2) for the period leading up to the amendment on 1
September 1996. At that stage when entitlement existed in 1994 and 1995 the Act
did not allow the Corporation to use the lessor divisor until the amendment of 1996.
Mr Thimbleby was not in receipt of weekly compensation as at 2 September 1996 and
therefore the amendment does not apply in his case."
[11] Mr Miller, counsel for the appellant at the hearing of the appeal, also appeared for him in
front of the review officer and made essentially the same submission there as he makes here
that :
"In terms of s 452 of the 1998 Act the amended section 40(2) should apply from
commencement of incapacity in 1994 and not the date the amended provision came
into force."
[12] The reviewer found that
"The following is common ground between the parties
Mr Thimbleby has had continuous entitlement to weekly compensation since 6
December 1994, he was therefore entitled to receive weekly compensation on 2
September 1996, the date upon which s 40(2)(a) became law.
Mr Thimbleby is a permanent employee for the purposes of s 40(2)(a)."
[13] Given that the Corporation accepted Mr Miller's submission that at worst the appellant was
entitled to the benefit of the recalculated earnings using the lessor divisor from 2 September
1996, the only matter for decision was whether or not the 1996 amendment had a retrospective
effect to the date of his accident.
[14] The review officer found that there is a legal presumption against retrospective effect of a
statute which is reinforced by s 7 of the Interpretation Act 1999. He also considered that the
intent of the statute was clear and that the Corporation was required to apply the Act "that
applied at that time when the decision being revised was made" (reviewer's emphasis). He
concluded that:
"If a provision was not in existence when the original decision was made then it
cannot be used in a subsequent revision decision unless a retrospective effect is
specified.'
[15] He therefore held that s. 40(2)(a) can only be applied from 2 September 1996 onwards.
[16] The appellant appealed against that decision on the grounds that it is wrong in law in that
the provisions of s.40(2)(a) should apply from the commencement of the incapacity period.
The Legislation
[17] Prior to September 1996 s 40 provided:
This section applies only to earners who are earners immediately before the
commencement of the incapacity and who, during the 12 months immediately
preceding the commencement of the period of incapacity, had earnings as an
employee and who did not also have earnings other than as an employee.
The weekly earnings of any person to whom this section applies shall be -
In respect of each of the 4 weeks next following the first week of
incapacity, the earnings as an employee during the 4 weeks immediately
before the commencement of the incapacity divided by the number of full
and part weeks of remunerated employment as an employee during that
period:
In respect of any period of incapacity after the period referred to in
paragraph (a) of this subsection, the lessor of -
1/520 of the earnings of that person as an employee during
the 52 weeks immediately before the commencement of the
incapacity; or
ii)
the weekly earnings calculated under paragraph (a) of this
subsection.
Where during the 12 months immediately preceding the commencement of the
incapacity, an employee had more than 1 employer, the calculations made
under subsection (2) of this section shall be made separately and then be
combined.'
[18] From 2 September 1996 the amended s.40 provided as follows:
This section applies only to earners who are earners immediately before the
commencement of the incapacity and who, during the 12 months immediately
preceding the commencement of the period of incapacity, had earnings as an
employee and who did not also have earnings other than as an employee.
The weekly earnings of any person to whom this section applies shall be, -
(a) In respect of each of the 4 weeks next following the sixth day after the day
on which the incapacity first commenced, the person's earnings as an
employee during the 4 weeks immediately before the commencement of
the incapacity divided by the number of full and part weeks during which
the person earned those earnings as an employee during that 4-week
period
In respect of any weekly period of incapacity after the period referred to in
paragraph (a) of this subsection, if the person was in permanent
employment immediately before the commencement of the incapacity, the
person's earnings as an employee during the 52 weeks immediately
before the commencement of the incapacity, divided by -
The number of full or part weeks during which the person earned
those earnings as an employee during that 52-week period; or
ii)
Thirteen, -
Whichever is the greater..
In respect of any weekly period of incapacity after the period referred to in
paragraph (a) of this subsection, if the person was not in permanent employment
immediately before the commencement of the incapacity, 1/52" of the person's
earnings as an employee during the 52 weeks immediately before the
commencement of the incapacity.
[2(a) For the purposes of this section, a person shall be regarded as having been in
permanent employment if, in the opinion of the Corporation, that person would have
continued to receive earnings from that employment for a continuous period of more
than 12 months after the commencement of incapacity if the personal injury had not
occurred]."
[19] As Mr Corkill for the respondent points out the difference between the two sections relates
to the divisor to be used when calculating weekly earnings of an incapacitated employee. For
the purposes of this litigation it is the difference between dividing the appellant's agreed income
for the period in which he worked in the year of the accident (17 weeks) rather than the 52
weeks originally taken by the Corporation.
[20] Also relevant are the provisions of s 452 of the Accident Insurance Act 1988. It provides:
The Manager may revise any decision (including a decision about premiums)
made by the former Corporation if it appears to the Manager that the decision
was made in error, whatever the reason for the error.
In revising a decision, the manager must apply the Act that applied at the time
when the decision being revised was made.
A revision may -
(a) Amend the original decision; or
(b) Revoke the original decision and substitute a new decision.
Every amendment to a decision, and every substituted decision, is a fresh
decision.
Part 6 applies to every fresh decision made under this section."
Submissions for the Appellant
[21] In that statutory context Mr Miller for the appellant submits that the amended s 40(2) does
have retrospective effect by virtue of the provisions of s 452(2) because that provision requires
the Corporation
"In revising a decision the manager must apply the Act that applied at the time when
the decision being revised was made.'
[22] Counsel gives emphasis to the words "the Act" submitting that it refers to whichever of the
Acts meets that description be it 1972, 1982 or 1992 but contending that s 452(2) does not refer
to this specific sections in those Acts
'which may have been amended at various times during the currency of the Act."
23] It submitted that if it were to be the specific sections in force at the time which were
required to be considered it would involve
"a massive effort on the part of the ACC to keep track of all amendments in particular
in previous Act to apply the relevant version of that section at that particular time."
(24] Counsel further submits that by virtue of s 23 of the Interpretation Act 1999 any
amendment to an Act becomes part of the Act and therefore any reference to "the Act" includes
all of its "amendments"
(25] Adopting this reasoning counsel submits that in the 1992 Act it is only the new s 40(2)
which has any statutory force because it repealed the previous s 40(2). Counsel submits that
there is nothing in the 1996 Amendment Act which keeps alive the old s 40(2) either by way of
any transitional provisions, or necessary implication.
[26] Counsel further submits that in any event the wording of the amended s 40(2) makes it
clear that Parliament intended it to apply from the commencement of the incapacity pointing out
that the section does not provide that it is to apply only to claims lodged from the date of the
commencement of the amendment submitting that
"the whole thrust is to look back at the incapacity and earnings from employment at
the time of the accident.'
[27] Viewed in this way s 40(2) refers to incapacity whenever it occurred. In this case it is 5
December 1994 and it is from that date which by virtue of the amending section the Corporation
is required to recalculate the appellant's weekly compensation for that incapacity.
[28] As to the appropriate cannons of statutory interpretation s 7 of the Interpretation Act 1999
which was relied upon by the reviewer is subject to s 4 which makes it clear that the blunt
statement contained in s 7 must always yield as to the provisions of any other enactment or "the
context of the enactment requires a different interpretation"
[29] As Professor Burrows recently pointed out in a paper on the Interpretation Act 1999 the
new s 7 is:
"A coarse device to deal with what is really a very complex matter."
and goes on to say
" whether an enactment is retrospective depends upon
Its words and context
Whether a retrospective interpretation is fair and reasonable."
for which Professor Burrows cites Westminster Council v Haywood 2000 2 All ER 634 at
[30] The author goes on to say
"There is a mass of authority drawing a facile but not entirely useless distinction
between enactments affecting substance and enactments affecting procedure."
(31] In W v W CA117/99, Judgment 23 March 2000 the CA held that an amendment to the
Accident Compensation legislation allowing for punitive damages after a criminal conviction, had
etrospective effect because its very purpose was to overturn an earlier decision of the Court of
Appeal in Daniels v Thompson [1998] 3 NZLR 22.
(32] The difficulty of ascertaining the intent of Parliament in this area of the law is graphically
Ilustrated by R v Pora, CA225/00, Judgment 20 December 2000. In that case, notwithstanding
the unequivocal wording of the amending act that minimum sentences for home invasion applied
even if the offence was committed before those provisions took effect", the majority of the Court
held that the provisions of s 42 of the Criminal Justice Act 1985, which provided that
notwithstanding any other enactment the Court cannot impose any penalty it could not have
imposed when the offence was committed, prevailed having regard to the provisions of s 25G of
the Bill of Rights Act and s 7 of the Interpretation Act. The majority was particularly guided by
the fundamental principle that in construing a criminal statute providing for penalties it should not
have retrospective effect to offences committed before the Act was passed. The minority (Gault
Keith & McGrath JJ) found that the wording of s 24 of the amending legislation was too clear for
there to be doubt as to Parliament's intention that the penalties for home invasion be
retrospective.
[33] It is clear from R v Poumaka [2000] 2 NZLR 695 Comalco that it is no longer possible to
embark upon a consideration of questions of retrospectivity without having regard to the New
Zealand Bill of Rights Act, in particular s 6 which provides:
"Where an enactment can be given a meaning that is consistent with the rights and
freedoms contained in this Bill of Rights that meaning shall be preferred to any other
meaning."
[34] There are no Bill of Rights considerations in this case which could affect the interpretation
of the provision in question, and therefore it is possible to construe it by reference to previously
established principles and in particular having regard to the provisions of s 4(1)(b) of the
Interpretation Act.
[35] Mr Corkill for the respondent submits that the amendment in question is substantive and
not procedural contending that statutes affecting substantive rights are not "readily construed as
being retrospective" and for that he relies upon a passage from Burrows Statute Law in New
Zealand 20 Edition Chapter 18 at pages 362 and following.
[36] Counsel draws support from the decision of the Court of Appeal in Cross v Commissioner
of Inland Revenue (1994) 16 NZTC 11249 at 11252 where Richardson J said:
"The ultimate question is one of the construction of the statute. It involves weighing
retrospectivity concerns in determining the intention of Parliament as reflected in the
scheme and language of the legislation."
[37] Approaching the matter in that way Mr Corkill submits that to construe the statute as
contended for by the appellant would "impose a new duty namely the liability of the Corporation
o calculate weekly compensation in a different way". Counsel submits this would have fiscal
consequences for the Corporation which may well apply to a number of cases effectively
backdating claims for uncompensation in those cases to which the appellant's construction
would apply.
[38] Mr Corkill submits that a clear pointer to Parliament's intention as to the time from which
the amendment is to apply is to be found in s 1 of the Amendment Act. It provides in the Short
Title:
'(ii) except as provided in subsection 3 of this section
This Act shall come into force on the date on which it receives the royal assent.
(iii) Sections 13 and 27 of this Act and the amendments to ss 71 and 148 of the
principal Act and the schedule to this Act shall come into force on the 1st day of July
1997." (my emphasis)
[39] None of the sections referred to above have any relevance to this case and Mr Corkill
submits that all of the other provisions therefore take effect from the date of the Royal Assent,
Parliament having turned its mind to the matter of the date of commencement of the various
sections. Counsel submits that the appellant's argument must therefore fail.
[40] In general terms the respondent relies upon the presumption against retrospectivity for
example as captured by Fullegar J in Fisher v Hebburn Limited (1960) 105 CLR 188 at page 194
where the Judge said:
"There can be no doubt that the general rule is that an amending enactment or for that
matter any enactment is prima facie to be construed as having a prospective
operation only. That is to say it is prima facie to be construed as not attaching new
legal consequences to facts or events which occurred before its commencement. The
rule has been frequently applied to amending statutes relating to workers
compensation and it has often been held that such amendments apply only in respect
of 'accident' or 'injuries' appearing after their coming into force: the cases of Moakes v
Blackwell Colliery Limited [1925] 2KB 63 and Kraljevich Lakeview and Star Limited
(1945) 70 CLR 647 are familiar examples."
[41] This case was discussed by the Court of Appeal in Dean v Accident Compensation
Corporation [1982] 1 NZLR 750.
[42] That was a case not unlike the present where the Corporation argued that:
" in the absence of a clear intention to the contrary a statute will not be construed with
retrospective effect that any right to compensation under the Accident Compensation
Act accrues as at the time of injury by accident."
[43] In resolving the question in that case Woodhouse P at page 752 referred to a related
passage from Maxwell on the interpretation of statutes (12" edition 1969) at page 215 to the
following effect:
"Before the presumption against retrospective is applied the Court must be satisfied
that the statute is in fact retrospective.'
[44] In the words of Craies on Statute Law 6" Edition page 386
"A statute is retrospective when it takes away or impairs any vested right acquired
under existing laws or creates a new obligation or imposes a new duty or attaches a
new disability in respect to transactions or considerations already passed. Other
statutes even though they may relate to Acts or events which are passed, are not
retrospective in the sense in which the word is used for the purposes of the rule under
construction."
[45] In Dean the Court was able to resolve the matter by holding that the proposition contended
for by the appellant did not involve any question of retrospectivity.
[46] Woodhouse P. points out:
"The presumption of retrospectivity in the sense it has been used by the Courts and
the commentators does not arise simply because a later statute is capable of applying
to some earlier event." (my emphasis)
[47] Woodhouse P. cited with approval a passage from the Judgment of Fullegar J in Fisher to
the following effect:
"It would not be true to say that a retrospective effect can only be avoided by confining
the operation of such a statute to subsequently occurring accidents or injuries. It may
truly be said to operate prospectively only although its prospect begins so to speak
with some other event than accident or injury."
and:
"With respect we think that statement is an accurate expression of the true position
and when the last sentence is used to test the construction of s 114(1) of the Accident
Compensation Act it gives emphasis to the conclusion that the conditions contained in
the opening words of that subsection do have the special contingent significance to
which we have already referred.
They indicate and determine the event or the circumstance from which the provision
will operate prospectively. It is for that reason that any argument related to the so
called retrospective operation of the amendment disappears."
[48] That analysis places the emphasis upon the circumstance to which the amending
legislation is directed, whether that circumstance arises before the enactment of the amending
legislation or after. Viewed in that way then to relate the amending legislation back to some
earlier event or circumstance is not necessarily to offend the presumption against retrospectivity.
[49] That is the situation for which Mr Miller contends in this case. Counsel submits that by
virtue of s 23 of the Interpretation Act "any amending enactment is part of the enactment that it
amends".
[50] The old s 40(2) has been repealed and replaced by the new s 40(2). There is no saving
provision relating to the old s 40(2) that it continued to apply to claims prior to the date upon
which the amending act received the Royal Assent therefore it is the new s 40(2) which by virtue
of s 45(2) applies to the appellant's compensation entitlements.
[51] Counsel submits the new s 40(2) must apply to the appellant's circumstances by virtue of
subsection (1) which makes it clear that s 40
"applies to earners who are earners immediately before the commencement of the
incapacity and who during the 12 months immediately preceding the commencement
of the period of incapacity had earnings as an employee and who did not also have
earnings other than an employee." (my emphasis)
[52] As Mr Miller submits there is always a specific date upon which the earner suffers his
incapacity. In this case it is the 5 December 1994. That carries down to subsection (2) which
deals with the calculation of the claimant's weekly earnings. It prescribes that:
"(a) In respect of each of the four weeks next following the 6" day after the day on
which the incapacity first commenced, the person's earnings as an employee during
the four weeks immediately before the commencement of the incapacity ..." (my
emphasis)
[53] Once again the trigger date is the day on which the incapacity first commenced. That is an
ascertainable fact and there can at least for the purposes of a case such as this only be one
such date. Similarly with the provisions of subsection 2(b).
[54] It is significant that the amending act does not by its terms provide that it only applies to
claims lodged from the date that the statute received the Royal Assent, or indeed any other
date. The whole thrust is to look back at the date of the incapacity and the earnings from
employment as they were at the time of the accident.
[55] That is not to construe this statute retrospectively, it is merely to construe it upon its plain
terms referable to the date upon which the incapacity arose.
[56] I am therefore satisfied that the appellant's arguments must prevail and he is entitled to
have his earnings related compensation recalculated as from the date of his accident of 5
December 1994, applying the divisor specified in the amending legislation.
[57] Leave is reserved to either parties to apply if it is necessary to make more precise orders.
[58] Costs are reserved.
Methey Willy
A A P Willy
District Court Judge
